{{DISPLAYTITLE:List of ''Bleach'' soundtracks}} {{Infobox artist discography | Artist = ''[[Bleach (manga)|Bleach]]'' | Image = BleachAnimeLogo.jpg | Caption = The ''Bleach'' logo, as seen on many of the series' CD covers | Compilation = 37 | Singles = 49 | Soundtrack = 9 | Option = 13 | Option name = Drama CD | Option link = Drama CD | Option color = #FFA07A | 1Option = 3 | 1Option name = Rock musical | 1Option link = Rock musical | 1Option color = #B0C4DE | References = Yes | Ref link = References }} {{Nihongo|'''''[[Bleach (manga)|Bleach]]'''''|ブリーチ|Burīchi}} is a Japanese [[manga]] series written and illustrated by [[Tite Kubo]]. ''Bleach'' follows the adventures of high school student [[Ichigo Kurosaki]] after he obtains the powers of a {{Nihongo|[[List of Soul Reapers in Bleach|Soul Reaper]]|死神|Shinigami|literally, "[[Shinigami|Death God]]"}} from another Soul Reaper, [[Rukia Kuchiki]]. The ''Bleach'' discography primarily consists of the original soundtrack produced for the ''[[Bleach (anime)|Bleach]]'', an [[anime]] adaptation of the manga. The soundtrack was composed by [[Shirō Sagisu]] and released in eight volumes and an anniversary box set. Numerous soundtracks have been released in different collections and sets. A series of character song albums, best-of albums composed of the theme songs, [[rock musical]] albums and [[Radio drama in Japan|drama]] CDs have also been released, all by [[Sony Music Entertainment Japan]].
The ''Bleach'' anime opening and ending credits songs take from a diverse group of bands including [[Orange Range]], [[UVERworld]], [[High and Mighty Color]], [[Beat Crusaders]], [[Yui (singer)|YUI]], [[Aqua Timez]], [[Asian Kung-Fu Generation]], [[Kelun]], [[Scandal (Japanese band)|SCANDAL]], [[Porno Graffitti]], [[miwa]], [[Sid (band)|SID]], [[Vivid (band)|ViViD]], [[Rie Fu]], [[Home Made Kazoku]], [[Younha]], [[SunSet Swish]], [[Ikimono-gakari]], [[June (singer)|JUNE]], [[Mai Hoshimura]], [[OreSkaBand]], [[chatmonchy]], [[RSP (band)|RSP]], [[Lil'B (group)|Lil'B]], [[Pe'z|pe'zmoku]], [[Stereopony]], [[Tsuji Shion]], [[Sambomaster]], [[Spyair]], [[Aimer]] and many. Aqua Timez in particular was used for numerous theme songs throughout the course of the production.
The two albums from ''Bleach'' discography won the [[Japan Gold Disc Award]]s in category "Animation Album of the Year".<ref name="riaj07">{{cite web|url=http://www.riaj.or.jp/e/data/gdisc/2007.html |title=THE {{sic|21|th|nolink=yes}} JAPAN GOLD DISC AWARD 2007 |publisher=[[RIAJ]] |accessdate=June 1, 2014}}</ref><ref name="riaj09">{{cite web|url=http://www.riaj.or.jp/e/data/gdisc/2009.html|title=THE {{sic|23|th|nolink=yes}} JAPAN GOLD DISC AWARD 2009 |publisher=[[RIAJ]] |accessdate=June 1, 2014}}</ref>
